{{Use mdy dates|date=November 2011}} {{Infobox historian | image = | caption = | birth_name = Benjamin Isadore Schwartz | birth_date = {{birth date|1916|12|12}} | birth_place = | death_date ={{nowrap| {{death date and age|1999|11|14|1916|12|12}} }} | death_place = | alma_mater = [[Harvard University]]({{small|[[B.A.]], [[M.A.]], [[Ph.D.]] }}) | institutions = [[Harvard University]] | school_tradition = | influences = | influenced = | module = {{infobox Chinese | child = yes | t = 史華慈 | s = 史华慈 | p = Shī Huaci |}} }} '''Benjamin Isadore Schwartz''' (December 12, 1916 – November 14, 1999) was an [[United States|American]] academic, author and [[sinology|sinologist]].<ref name=ideas>{{cite book|last=Cohen|first=Paul A.|year=1990|publisher=Harvard University Asia Center|isbn=978-0-674-44225-2|author2=Merle Goldman|accessdate=March 20, 2011|title=Ideas across cultures: essays on Chinese thought in honor of Benjamin I. Schwartz|pages=1–7|chapter=Introduction | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ORB3-x9TKQUC&lpg=PA317&dq=%22world%20of%20thought%20in%20ancient%20china%22&pg=PA1#v=onepage&q=%22world%20of%20thought%20in%20ancient%20china%22&f=false}}</ref><ref name=NYTobit>{{cite news|last=Butterfield|first=Fox|authorlink=Fox Butterfield|title=Benjamin Schwartz, 82, Dies; Expert on Mao's Revolution|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1999/11/18/world/benjamin-schwartz-82-dies-expert-on-mao-s-revolution.html?src=pm|accessdate=March 20, 2011|newspaper=[[New York Times]]|date=November 18, 1999}}</ref>
==Educational background== Schwartz graduated from [[Harvard University]] in 1938 in modern languages, with an honors thesis on ''Pascal and the XVIIIth century "philosophes"'' <ref>[http://www.worldcat.org/title/pascal-and-the-xviiith-century-philosophes/oclc/76997189&referer=brief_results WorldCat record for Schwartz's thesis]</ref> and started a career in school teaching before studying [[Japanese language|Japanese]] during the [[Second World War]] and working on code-breaking. After the war he studied an M.A. in East Asian studies at Harvard and went on to gain a Ph.D. there.<ref name=ideas />
==Career== Schwartz was a member of the Harvard faculty, teaching in Cambridge until he retired in 1987.
In 1983-1984, Schwartz served as acting director of the [[Fairbank Center for Chinese Studies]].<ref>Suleski, Ronald Stanley. (2005). ''The Fairbank Center for East Asian Research at Harvard University,'' p. 76.</ref>
A [[festschrift]] in his honour was held after his retirement, and published in 1990 as ''Ideas across cultures: essays on Chinese thought in honor of Benjamin I. Schwartz'' ({{ISBN|978-0-674-44225-2}}) and published by the [[Harvard University Asia Center]].
He wrote principally on recent situations in China. His first book in that area was ''Chinese communism and the rise of Mao'' (1951), held in 1546 academic libraries.<ref>[http://www.worldcat.org/title/chinese-communism-and-the-rise-of-mao/oclc/412849&referer=brief_results WorldCat record for ''Chinese Communism and the Rise of Mao'']</ref> He subsequently wrote: ''Communism and China; ideology in flux'' published by Harvard University Press in 1968, held in 929 libraries according to [[WorldCat]],<ref>[http://www.worldcat.org/title/communism-and-china-ideology-in-flux/oclc/266545&referer=brief_results WorldCat record for ''Communism and China'']</ref> and edited the symposium ''Reflections on the May Fourth movement: a symposium.'' East Asian Research Center, Harvard University; distributed by Harvard University Press, 1972.<ref>[http://www.worldcat.org/title/reflections-on-the-may-fourth-movement-a-symposium/oclc/509380&referer=brief_results WorldCat record for ''Reflections on the May Fourth Movement'']</ref> Near the end of his career in 1996 he wrote ''China and Other Matters'' Cambridge, Massachusetts: Harvard University Press <ref>[http://www.worldcat.org/title/china-and-other-matters/oclc/33818896&referer=brief_results WorldCat record for ''China and Other Matters'']</ref>
He also wrote on earlier periods. His 1985 book ''The World of Thought in Ancient China'' was published by Harvard University Press, and is held in 850 libraries, according to [http://www.worldcat.org/title/world-of-thought-in-ancient-china/oclc/11728257&referer=brief_results WorldCat]. It was reviewed in ''[[The American Historical Review]]'',<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Crawford|first1=Robert B.|title=Benjamin I. Schwartz. ''The World of Thought in Ancient China''|journal=The American Historical Review|date=June 1987|volume=92|issue=3|pages=720–721|doi=10.1086/ahr/92.3.720|department=Review}}</ref> ''[[Bulletin of the School of Oriental and African Studies]]'',<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Barrett|first1=T. H.|title=Benjamin I. Schwartz: ''The world of thought in ancient China''|journal=Bulletin of the School of Oriental and African Studies|date=1988|volume=51|issue=2|pages=370–371|doi=10.1017/S0041977X00115101|department=Review}}</ref> ''[[Harvard Journal of Asiatic Studies]]'',<ref>[http://www.worldcat.org/title/review-of-the-world-of-thought-in-ancient-china/oclc/486491956&referer=brief_results Harvard Journal of Asiatic Studies]</ref> ''[[China Quarterly]]'',<ref>[http://www.worldcat.org/title/review-of-the-world-of-thought-in-ancient-china/oclc/479363438&referer=brief_results China Quarterly Mar., 1988, no. 113, p. 132-134]</ref> ''[[The Journal of Asian Studies]]'',<ref>[http://www.worldcat.org/title/review-of-the-world-of-thought-in-ancient-china/oclc/484614880&referer=brief_results The Journal of Asian Studies, Aug., 1988, vol. 47, no. 3, p. 621-623]</ref> ''[[Philosophy East and West]]'',<ref>[http://www.worldcat.org/title/review-of-the-world-of-thought-in-ancient-china/oclc/486120018&referer=brief_results ''Philosophy East and West'', Oct., 1988, vol. 38, no. 4, p. 411-419]</ref> '' Chinese Literature: Essays, Articles, Reviews'',<ref>Chinese Literature: Essays, Articles, Reviews, Jul., 1987, vol. 9, no. 1/2, p. 161 [http://www.worldcat.org/title/review-of-the-world-of-thought-in-ancient-china/oclc/481460351&referer=brief_results]</ref> and ''[[The Australian Journal of Chinese Affairs]]''.<ref>The Australian Journal of Chinese Affairs, Jan., 1986, no. 15, p. 150-153.</ref>
==Selected works== * ''Chinese Communism and the Rise of Mao'' (Cambridge: Cambridge University Press, 1951). * {{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=hnQoD4bIXCwC&printsec=frontcover&dq=Benjamin+I.+Schwartz&hl=en&sa=X&ei=jHo_UYjgGZKN0QHpjIHwBg&ved=0CEsQ6AEwAw#v=onepage&q=Benjamin%20I.%20Schwartz&f=false|title=In Search of Wealth and Power: Yen Fu and the West|place=Cambridge, Massachusetts|publisher=Harvard University Press|year=1964|isbn=9780674446526}}; Harvard University Press, 2009, {{ISBN|9780674043329}} * ''Communism and China: Ideology in Flux'' (Cambridge, Massachusetts: Harvard University Press, 1968). * {{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=kA0c1hl3CXUC&printsec=frontcover&dq=Benjamin+I.+Schwartz&hl=en&sa=X&ei=jHo_UYjgGZKN0QHpjIHwBg&ved=0CDgQ6AEwAA#|title=The World of Thought in Ancient China|place=Cambridge, Massachusetts|publisher=Harvard University Press|year=1985|isbn=9780674961913}}; Harvard University Press, 2009, {{ISBN|9780674043312}} * ''The secret speeches of Chairman Mao : from the hundred flowers to the great leap forward by Zedong Mao'' (1989) * ''Reflections on the May Fourth movement: a symposium'', East Asian Research Center, Harvard University, 1972. * ''China's Cultural Values'', Center for Asian Studies, Arizona State University, 1985 * {{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Wt4XDLEpjWYC&printsec=frontcover&dq=Benjamin+I.+Schwartz&hl=en&sa=X&ei=jHo_UYjgGZKN0QHpjIHwBg&ved=0CD4Q6AEwAQ#v=onepage&q=Benjamin%20I.%20Schwartz&f=false|title=China and Other Matters|place=Cambridge, Massachusetts|publisher=Harvard University Press|year=1996|isbn=9780674118621}}
